<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 2.3 - The Span of a Set of Vectors</title>
  
<definition>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The <em>span</em> of a set of vectors <m>\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \ldots, \vvec_n</m>
      is the set of all linear combinations that can be formed from the vectors.
    </p>
    <p>
      Alternatively, if <m>{A = \left[\vvec_1 \,\,\, \vvec_2 \,\,\, \cdots \,\,\, \vvec_n\right],}</m>
      then the span of the vectors consists of all vectors <m>\bvec</m> for which the equation
      <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m> is consistent.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        <term>The setting:</term> You are a young traveler, leaving home for the first time. Your parents
        want to help you on your journey, so just before your departure, they give you two gifts.
        Specifically, they give you two forms of transportation: a hoverboard and a magic carpet. Your parents
        inform you that the hoverboard and the magic carpet have restrictions in how they operate.
      </p>
      <p>
        <term>Hoverboard's Restrictions:</term> We denote the restriction on the hoverboard's movement 
        by the vector <m>\vvec = \twovec{3}{1}</m>. By this we mean that if the hoverboard traveled
        "forward" for one hour, it would move along a "diagonal" path that would result in a displacement
        of 3 miles East and 1 mile North of its starting location.  You can also put it in reverse - after one
        hour you'd be 3 miles West and 1 mile South.
      </p>
      <p>
        <term>Magic Carpet's Restrictions:</term> We denote the restriction on the magic carpet's movement 
        by the vector <m>\wvec = \twovec{1}{2}</m>. By this we mean that if the magic carpet traveled
        "forward" for one hour, it would move along a "diagonal" path that would result in a displacement
        of 1 mile East and 2 miles North of its starting location.  You can also take this in reverse as well.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Use the tape to mark the origin and <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axis.  Each tile is one unit. You've made a "floor plane."</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        (INCLUDE A PICTURE HERE OF THE FLOOR! Or maybe Prefigure picture?)
      </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Travel with the hoverboard for one hour, and then travel with the magic carpet forward for one hour. Where do you end up?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          (INCLUDE A PICTURE HERE OF THE FLOOR! Or maybe Prefigure picture?) <m>\twovec{3}{1} + \twovec{1}{2} = \twovec{4}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Now do the opposite - travel with the magic carpet forward for one hour, and then travel with the hoverboard 
          forward for one hour. Where do you end up? What does this say about <m>\vvec+\wvec</m> vs. <m>\wvec+\vvec</m>?
          Does this hold in general?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          (INCLUDE A PICTURE HERE OF THE FLOOR! Or maybe Prefigure picture?) <m>\twovec{1}{2} + \twovec{3}{1} = \twovec{4}{3}</m>.
          So, <m>\vvec + \wvec = \wvec + \vvec</m> and this holds in general!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Where do you end up if you travel in the reverse direction on your magic carpet for 1.5 hours?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          (INCLUDE A PICTURE HERE OF THE FLOOR! Or maybe Prefigure picture?) <m>(-1.5)\twovec{1}{2} = \twovec{-1.5}{-3}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          You lost your magic carpet. Starting at the origin and using just your hoverboard, can you get
          to your friend's house at <m>\twovec{-6}{-2}</m>? Can you get to the grocery store at <m>\twovec{2}{4}</m>?
          How would you describe the collection of places you can get to? (I.e., is it a point or a line or all of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>?)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To get to your friend's house, you need to travel backwards for 2 hours.
          <m>(-2)\twovec{3}{1} = \twovec{-6}{-2}</m>. But, you can't get to the grocery store
          because there is no value <m>x</m> such that <m>x\twovec{3}{1} = \twovec{3x}{x} = \twovec{2}{4}</m>.
          Therefore, <m>\twovec{3x}{x} \neq \twovec{2}{4}</m> for any <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Good news, you're back at the origin, and you have both your magic carpet and your hoverboard. You want to go visit the wise man,
          Old Man Gauss, who lives in a cabin that is 107 miles East and 64 miles North of your home. Is it possible to get there?
          If so, express how using a linear combination/vector notation. If not, explain why not. Is there more than one way to get there?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To answer this, let's set up a linear combination and solve the corresponding linear system! First,
          <md>
            x_1\twovec{3}{1} + x_2\twovec{1}{2} = \twovec{107}{64}.
          </md>
          Then, 
          <md>
            \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      3 \amp  1 \amp 107 \\
      1 \amp  2 \amp 64 \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \sim \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp  0 \amp 30 \\
      0 \amp  1 \amp 17 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
          </md>
          So, 30 hours on the hoverboard and 17 on the magic carpet will get you there!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Old Man Gauss now tries to hide somewhere you can't visit him. Is there somewhere he could hide? How would you describe a collection of places you can get to?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          He can't hide. Consider the augmented system <md>
            \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      3 \amp  1 \amp x \\
      1 \amp  2 \amp y \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \sim \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp  0 \amp * \\
      0 \amp  1 \amp * \\
    \end{array}
  \right]</md>
        This system is always consistent and therefore, always has a solutions! We can get anywhere in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Your cousin also gets a magic carpet and a hoverboard from your aunt and uncle. His magic carpet also travels in the direction
          <m>\vvec = \twovec{3}{1}</m>, but his hoverboard travels in the direction <m>\uvec = \twovec{6}{2}</m>.  Use your 
          "floor plane" to determine where your cousin can go.  Can Old Man Gauss hide from your friend?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          My cousin can only travel along a line since <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\uvec</m> are scalar multiples
          of each other. Specifically, my cousin only travels along the line <m>{y = \frac{1}{3}x}</m>.
        </p>
        <image>
<shortdescription>Graph of <m>f(x) = \frac{-1}{2}x^2 - \frac{3}{2}x + 14</m> going through the 3 given points.</shortdescription>
<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="09-2-3_1">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
  <definition>f(x)=(1/3)*x</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-2,-2,8,4)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
    <point p="(3,1)" alignment="nw">
      <m>(3,1)</m>
    </point>
    <point p="(6,2)" alignment="nw">
      <m>(6,2)</m>
    </point>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let's put some more technical terms to the magic carpet/hoverboard scenario. Recall the following movement:
        <ul>
          <li><p>You and your cousin's hoverboard travel in the direction <m>\vvec = \twovec{3}{1}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Your magic carpet can move in the direction <m>\wvec = \twovec{1}{2}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Your cousin's magic carpet can move in the direction <m>\uvec = \twovec{6}{2}</m>.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Describe the set of vectors that result from linear combinations of <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\wvec</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          All of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Describe the set of vectors that result from linear combinations of <m>\vvec</m> and <m>\uvec</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A line, with the slope 1/3, going through the origin.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is Span<m>\{\vvec,\wvec\}</m>? Try to describe geometrically and algebraically.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Geometrically, this is all of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.  Algebraically, this is 
          <m>{a\twovec{3}{1} + b\twovec{1}{2}}</m> for any real number <m>a, b</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is Span<m>\{\vvec,\uvec\}</m>? Try to describe geometrically and algebraically.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
      <p>
          Geometrically, this is a line.  Algebraically, this is 
          <m>{a\twovec{3}{1}}</m> for any real number <m>a</m>. Note,
          that we don't need the <m>\uvec</m> because it is a scalar multiple of <m>\vvec</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For what vectors <m>\bvec</m> does the matrix equation <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 1  \\
      1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]\xvec = \bvec</m> have a solution?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          All vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.  
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For what vectors <m>\bvec</m> does the matrix equation <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 6  \\
      1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]\xvec = \bvec</m> have a solution?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          All vectors <m>\bvec = \twovec{3x}{x}</m> for any value <m>x</m> (a line). 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many pivots does the matrix <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 1  \\
      1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]</m> have? How might this be related to your answer for Span<m>\{\vvec,\wvec\}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The row
          reduced echelon form of <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 1  \\
      1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]</m> is the identity matrix, which means that the system is always consistent,
  no matter what <m>\bvec</m> is.  There is a pivot in every row!
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many pivots does the matrix <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 6  \\
      1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]</m> have? How might this be related to your answer for Span<m>\{\vvec,\uvec\}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The row
          reduced echelon form of <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      3 \amp 1  \\
      1 \amp 2 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]</m> is <m>\left[
    \begin{array}{rr}
      1 \amp 2  \\
      0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]</m>, which means that there is only 1 pivot and thus, not always a solution.
  For some <m>\bvec</m> there could be a pivot in the rightmost column of the augmented matrix
  for the corresponding linear system, thus resulting in no solution.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  
  <outcomes>
    <ul>
      <li><p>What is the span of a set of vectors and how do we denote it?</p></li>
      <li><p>How can we determine if a vector is in the span of another set of vectors?</p></li>
      <li><p>How do we know if the span of a set of vectors <m>\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \dots, \vvec_n</m> is <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m> using the pivots of the matrix <m>[\vvec_1 \,\,\, \vvec_2 \,\,\, \vvec_3 \,\,\, \dots \,\,\, \vvec_n]</m>?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </outcomes>

</worksheet>
